<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  Chapter 10 - Natural Deduction

  Draft status:
  - First full draft of the first natural deduction chapter.
  - Introduces proof layout, the goal of a derivation, and the eight
    implication rules.
  - Proof examples follow the compact Exam 3 answer-key style: numbered
    lines, the conclusion after a slash in the premise block, and
    justifications by line number plus rule abbreviation.
  - Replacement rules, conditional proof, and indirect proof are reserved
    for later chapters, except for a brief Double Negation preview in one
    answer-key-style proof.
-->
<chapter xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" xml:id="ch-natural-deduction">

  <title>Natural Deduction</title>

  <introduction xml:id="ch-natural-deduction-intro">
    <p>
      Truth tables gave us a mechanical test for validity. They tell us
      whether a symbolic argument has a counterexample row. Natural
      deduction asks a different question: can we get from the premises
      to the conclusion one small, justified step at a time?
    </p>
    <p>
      The style for this course is intentionally compact. A
      proof is a numbered list of lines. Premises go first. The target
      conclusion appears after a slash. Every line after the premises
      must cite earlier line numbers and a rule abbreviation. A finished
      proof ends when the target conclusion appears as a justified line.
    </p>
  </introduction>

  <section xml:id="sec-what-natural-deduction-does">
    <title>What Natural Deduction Does</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        A truth table checks validity all at once. A natural deduction
        proof shows validity step by step.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <definition xml:id="def-natural-deduction-proof">
      <statement>
        <p>
          A <term>natural deduction proof</term> is a sequence of
          statements in which each non-premise line is licensed by a rule
          of inference applied to earlier lines.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </definition>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-proof-not-discovery">
      <title>Proof is not the same as discovery</title>
      <p>
        When you work a proof, you may try lines that go nowhere. That
        is normal. A submitted proof does not have to look like the
        shortest possible path to the conclusion. But every line in it
        must be legitimate: each non-premise line must be genuinely
        justified by the rules from earlier lines.
      </p>
      <p>
        The rules are strict. You cannot write a line just because it
        feels obvious. You have to be able to point to earlier lines and
        say which rule permits the new line.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-compared-with-truth-tables">
      <title>Why proofs after truth tables?</title>
      <p>
        Truth tables are complete for sentential logic, but they get
        large quickly. An argument with five different sentence letters
        requires thirty-two rows. An argument with six requires
        sixty-four. Natural deduction can often show the same validity
        much more directly.
      </p>
      <p>
        Proofs also make the structure of an argument visible. A truth
        table tells you that an argument is valid. A proof shows how the
        conclusion is forced by the premises.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-anatomy-of-a-proof">
    <title>The Anatomy of a Proof</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Every proof in this chapter has three parts: line numbers,
        formulas, and justifications.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-proof-layout">
      <title>The basic layout</title>
      <p>
        Here is the format we'll use in the course:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-nd-basic-layout">
        <title>A Basic Natural Deduction Layout</title>
        <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
          <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
          <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>Q</m></cell><cell>1,2 MP</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Lines 1 and 2 are premises. The slash on line 2 marks the target:
        prove <m>Q</m>. Line 3 is the conclusion, and the justification
        tells us why it is allowed: lines 1 and 2 by Modus Ponens.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-why-abstract-rules">
      <title>Why abstract away?</title>
      <p>
        That first proof is a particular application of Modus Ponens. But
        the rule is not really about the specific letters <m>P</m> and
        <m>Q</m>. It is about a pattern: if we have a conditional, and we
        also have that conditional's antecedent, then we may infer its
        consequent.
      </p>
      <p>
        To state that pattern clearly, we need to talk about formulas
        without naming one particular formula every time. The symbols
        <m>P</m>, <m>Q</m>, <m>R</m>, <m>\supset</m>, <m>\cdot</m>,
        <m>\lor</m>, <m>\equiv</m>, and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m> belong to the symbolic language
        we are studying. Call that the <term>object language</term>.
      </p>
      <p>
        To talk about formulas of that language in a more general way,
        we will use a small <term>metalanguage</term>. The letters
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, <m>\mathcal{C}</m>, and
        <m>\mathcal{D}</m> are not sentence letters. They are
        <term>metavariables</term>: placeholders for any well-formed
        formula.
      </p>
      <p>
        So <m>\mathcal{A}</m> might stand for <m>P</m>. It might also
        stand for <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>, or
        <m>(R \lor S) \supset T</m>, or any other well-formed formula.
        This lets us state a rule once and then recognize many different
        applications of it.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-justifications">
      <title>Justifications</title>
      <p>
        A justification has two pieces. First, cite the line or lines you
        used. Second, name the rule. For example, <q>1,2 MP</q> means
        that line 3 follows from lines 1 and 2 by Modus Ponens.
      </p>
      <p>
        A one-line rule cites one earlier line. A two-line rule cites two
        earlier lines. A three-line rule cites three earlier lines. The
        order of the citations should make the rule easy to check, but
        the deeper habit is this: every derived line must be traceable
        to something already written.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-target-line">
      <title>The slash is the target</title>
      <p>
        The formula after the slash is not another premise. It is what
        you are trying to prove.  The conclusion is written on the same line as the final premise:
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-nd-target-line">
        <title>Premises and Target</title>
        <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
          <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
          <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        This says: given <m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m> and
        <m>S</m>, prove <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>. The proof is
        not complete until <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m> appears on a
        numbered line with a correct justification.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-eight-implication-rules">
    <title>The Eight Implication Rules</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The first group of natural deduction rules is called the
        implication rules. The name is historical. Not all of them use
        the horseshoe. What they have in common is that they permit
        direct moves from earlier lines to a new line.
      </p>
      <p>
        The rules below are written as schemas. The metavariables
        <m>\mathcal{A}</m>, <m>\mathcal{B}</m>, <m>\mathcal{C}</m>, and
        <m>\mathcal{D}</m> may be replaced by any well-formed formulas,
        as long as the same metavariable is replaced by the same formula
        throughout that instance of the rule.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-mp-mt">
      <title>Modus Ponens and Modus Tollens</title>
      <p>
        <term>Modus Ponens</term> (MP) says that if you have a
        conditional and you have its antecedent, you may infer its
        consequent.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-mp">
        <title>Modus Ponens Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        The proof above with <m>P \supset Q</m>, <m>P</m>, and
        <m>Q</m> is one <term>substitution instance</term> of this
        schema: replace <m>\mathcal{A}</m> with <m>P</m> and
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m> with <m>Q</m>. But the antecedent and
        consequent do not have to be single sentence letters.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-mp-compound-instance">
        <title>A Compound Instance of Modus Ponens</title>
        <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
          <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
          <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q) \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>R</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>R</m></cell><cell>2,1 MP</cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        In this instance, <m>\mathcal{A}</m> is
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}(P \cdot Q)</m>, and
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m> is <m>R</m>. The order of the cited lines
        does not change the logical point. What matters is that one line
        has the form <m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m> and the
        other line is that same <m>\mathcal{A}</m>. Then MP permits
        <m>\mathcal{B}</m>.
      </p>
      <p>
        <term>Modus Tollens</term> (MT) says that if you have a
        conditional and you have the negation of its consequent, you may
        infer the negation of its antecedent.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-mt">
        <title>Modus Tollens Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        Do not confuse MT with the invalid move of affirming the
        consequent. From <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>Q</m>, you cannot
        infer <m>P</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-hs-ds">
      <title>Hypothetical Syllogism and Disjunctive Syllogism</title>
      <p>
        <term>Hypothetical Syllogism</term> (HS) chains conditionals.
        If one conditional takes you from <m>P</m> to <m>Q</m>, and
        another takes you from <m>Q</m> to <m>R</m>, you may infer the
        direct conditional from <m>P</m> to <m>R</m>.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-hs">
        <title>Hypothetical Syllogism Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{B} \supset \mathcal{C}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{C}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        <term>Disjunctive Syllogism</term> (DS) uses a disjunction and
        the denial of one disjunct to infer the other.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-ds">
        <title>Disjunctive Syllogism Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        DS works on either side. From <m>P \lor Q</m> and
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>, you may infer <m>P</m>.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-simp-conj-add">
      <title>Simplification, Conjunction, and Addition</title>
      <p>
        <term>Simplification</term> (Simp) lets you take either part of
        a conjunction.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-simp">
        <title>Simplification Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        <term>Conjunction</term> (Conj) lets you join two available
        lines with a dot.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-conj">
        <title>Conjunction Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        <term>Addition</term> (Add) lets you introduce a disjunction
        from a line you already have. This rule feels strange at first,
        but it is truth-preserving: if <m>P</m> is true, then
        <m>P \lor Q</m> is true no matter what <m>Q</m> is.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-add">
        <title>Addition Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{A}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-cd">
      <title>Constructive Dilemma</title>
      <p>
        <term>Constructive Dilemma</term> (CD) is the longest of the
        eight implication rules. It uses two conditionals and a
        disjunction of their antecedents to infer a disjunction of their
        consequents.
      </p>
      <table xml:id="table-rule-cd">
        <title>Constructive Dilemma Schema</title>
        <tabular halign="center" margins="0% 70%">
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{A} \supset \mathcal{B}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{C} \supset \mathcal{D}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell bottom="medium"><m>\mathcal{A} \lor \mathcal{C}</m></cell></row>
          <row><cell><m>\mathcal{B} \lor \mathcal{D}</m></cell></row>
        </tabular>
      </table>
      <p>
        CD is useful when an argument says, in effect, either the first
        route is open or the second route is open; if the first route is
        open, one result follows; if the second route is open, another
        result follows; so one of those results follows.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-appendix-reference">
      <title>Quick reference</title>
      <p>
        All eight implication rules — together with the ten
        replacement rules from the next chapter — are collected in
        <xref ref="appendix-rules-of-inference"/> for quick
        reference. You may want to bookmark that appendix as you
        work through the exercises.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-first-worked-proofs">
    <title>First Worked Proofs</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        The easiest way to learn proofs is to watch the rules in action and then try them yourself.
       
      </p>
      <p>
        The first example briefly uses Double Negation (DN), a replacement
        rule covered systematically in the next chapter. It is included
        here because this is a common move in the course's worked proofs.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <example xml:id="ex-nd-mt-with-double-negation">
      <title>A short Modus Tollens proof</title>
      <statement>
        <table xml:id="table-ex-nd-mt-with-double-negation">
          <title>Deriving <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></title>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset {\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>S</m></cell><cell>/ <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m></cell><cell>2 DN</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>1,3 MT</cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Line 1 says that <m>P</m> would give us
      <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>. Line 2 gives us <m>S</m>. To use
      MT, we need the negation of the consequent of line 1, which is
      <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}{\text{\textasciitilde}}S</m>. Line 3
      gets that by Double Negation. Then MT gives the target
      <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-nd-simp-mp-conj">
      <title>Building a conjunction</title>
      <statement>
        <table xml:id="table-ex-nd-simp-mp-conj">
          <title>Deriving <m>P \cdot S</m></title>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \lor R) \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \cdot S</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>2 Simp</cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell>3 Add</cell></row>
            <row><cell>5.</cell><cell><m>S</m></cell><cell>1,4 MP</cell></row>
            <row><cell>6.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot S</m></cell><cell>3,5 Conj</cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      This proof works backward from the target. To prove
      <m>P \cdot S</m>, we need <m>P</m> and <m>S</m>. Line 2 gives
      <m>P</m> by Simplification. To get <m>S</m>, line 1 needs
      <m>P \lor R</m>. Since we already have <m>P</m>, Addition gives
      <m>P \lor R</m>, and then MP gives <m>S</m>.
    </p>

    <example xml:id="ex-nd-constructive-dilemma">
      <title>A constructive dilemma</title>
      <statement>
        <table xml:id="table-ex-nd-constructive-dilemma">
          <title>Deriving <m>S \lor I</m></title>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>F \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}F \supset I</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>F \lor {\text{\textasciitilde}}F</m></cell><cell>/ <m>S \lor I</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>4.</cell><cell><m>S \lor I</m></cell><cell>1,2,3 CD</cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </table>
      </statement>
    </example>
    <p>
      Constructive Dilemma is a three-line rule. Line 3 gives the
      disjunction of the antecedents from lines 1 and 2. So CD allows
      the disjunction of the consequents, <m>S \lor I</m>.
    </p>

  </section>

  <section xml:id="sec-basic-proof-strategy">
    <title>Basic Proof Strategy</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        There is no single recipe for every proof, but there are good
        habits.
      </p>
    </introduction>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-work-backward">
      <title>Look at the target first</title>
      <p>
        If the target is a conjunction, expect to prove each side and
        then use Conj. If the target is a disjunction, see whether you
        can get one side and use Add, or whether DS or CD will give you
        the whole disjunction. If the target is a negation, look for MT
        or DS.
      </p>
      <p>
        In other words, try to match the target to the output line of a
        rule schema. If the target has the form
        <m>\mathcal{A} \cdot \mathcal{B}</m>, Conj is a natural
        candidate. If the target has the form
        <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}\mathcal{A}</m>, MT may be relevant.
        The schemas turn strategy into pattern matching.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-mine-premises">
      <title>Mine the premises</title>
      <p>
        Conjunctions are often useful because Simp lets you extract
        their parts. Conditionals are useful when you can find their
        antecedents. Disjunctions are useful when one disjunct has been
        ruled out.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-do-not-overwrite-lines">
      <title>Do not change old lines</title>
      <p>
        A proof does not transform a line by erasing it. If you use a
        rule, write the result on a new line. The old line stays where it
        is. This is why line numbers matter: they let another reader see
        the exact path from premises to conclusion.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <paragraphs xml:id="paragraphs-nd-when-stuck">
      <title>When you are stuck</title>
      <p>
        Ask three questions. First, what shape is the conclusion?
        Second, which rule could produce a line of that shape? Third,
        what earlier lines would that rule need? This turns proof search
        from a guessing game into a small planning problem.
      </p>
    </paragraphs>

    <exploration xml:id="field-10-5-1">
      <title>Field Exercise: Narrate a proof</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Choose one of the harder proofs from this chapter's
          exercises — one that took you more than one attempt.
          After you have a finished proof, write a short narrative
          of your process. What did you try first? Where did you get
          stuck? What move got you unstuck? The goal is not to
          explain the proof to someone else but to observe your own
          reasoning while it is still fresh.
        </p>
      </statement>
    </exploration>

  </section>
  <section xml:id="sec-natural-deduction-where-headed">
    <title>Where We're Headed</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced the basic proof format and the eight
      implication rules. Those rules are enough for many short proofs,
      especially when the conclusion follows directly from conditionals,
      conjunctions, and disjunctions already present in the premises.
    </p>
    <p>
      The next natural deduction chapter adds the replacement rules.
      Replacement rules let us rewrite a statement into an equivalent
      form. They are especially important for De Morgan transformations,
      double negation, material implication, and material equivalence.
    </p>

  </section>

  <conclusion xml:id="conclusion-ch-natural-deduction">
    <title>Chapter Summary</title>

    <p>
      This chapter introduced natural deduction as a method for proving
      sentential arguments valid.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>What Natural Deduction Does (§10.1).</alert> Natural
      deduction shows that a conclusion follows by deriving it from the
      premises one rule-governed step at a time.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Anatomy of a Proof (§10.2).</alert> A proof has
      numbered lines, formulas, and justifications. In this course's
      compact format, the target conclusion appears after a slash in the
      premise block. After the first concrete proof, we introduce
      metavariables so that rules can be stated as general schemas rather
      than as single examples.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>The Eight Implication Rules (§10.3).</alert> MP, MT, HS,
      DS, Simp, Conj, Add, and CD are direct inference rules. Each is
      stated as a schema that can have many substitution instances.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>First Worked Proofs (§10.4).</alert> Short proofs often
      combine several rules: simplify conjunctions, use addition to make
      useful disjunctions, apply MP or MT to conditionals, and use Conj
      to assemble a conjunctive target.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Basic Proof Strategy (§10.5).</alert> Work backward from
      the target, match formulas to rule schemas, mine the premises for
      usable parts, and write every result on a new numbered line.
    </p>

  </conclusion>

  <section xml:id="sec-ch10-key-terms">
    <title>Key Terms</title>

    <p>Listed alphabetically, with section references.</p>

    <dl>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-addition">
        <title>Addition</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits inferring <m>P \lor Q</m> from <m>P</m>. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-conjunction">
        <title>Conjunction</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits joining two available lines as a conjunction. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-constructive-dilemma">
        <title>Constructive Dilemma</title>
        <p>An implication rule that uses two conditionals and a disjunction of their antecedents to infer a disjunction of their consequents. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-disjunctive-syllogism">
        <title>Disjunctive Syllogism</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits inferring one disjunct from a disjunction and the negation of the other disjunct. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-hypothetical-syllogism">
        <title>Hypothetical Syllogism</title>
        <p>An implication rule that chains two conditionals into a new conditional. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-instantiation">
        <title>Instantiation</title>
        <p>Another name for a substitution instance: a particular use of a general rule schema. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-justification">
        <title>Justification</title>
        <p>The citation on a proof line that names the earlier line or lines used and the rule applied. (§10.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-metalanguage">
        <title>Metalanguage</title>
        <p>A language used to talk about another language. In this chapter, metavariables such as <m>\mathcal{A}</m> and <m>\mathcal{B}</m> let us talk generally about formulas of sentential logic. (§10.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-metavariable">
        <title>Metavariable</title>
        <p>A placeholder in the metalanguage that can stand for any well-formed formula of the object language. (§10.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-modus-ponens">
        <title>Modus Ponens</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits inferring the consequent of a conditional when the antecedent is given. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-modus-tollens">
        <title>Modus Tollens</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits inferring the negation of a conditional's antecedent when the negation of its consequent is given. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-natural-deduction-proof">
        <title>Natural deduction proof</title>
        <p>A numbered derivation in which each non-premise line follows from earlier lines by a stated rule. (§10.1)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-object-language">
        <title>Object language</title>
        <p>The symbolic language being studied, including sentence letters and connectives such as <m>\supset</m>, <m>\cdot</m>, <m>\lor</m>, <m>\equiv</m>, and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}</m>. (§10.2)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-rule-schema">
        <title>Rule schema</title>
        <p>A general statement of a rule using metavariables rather than one particular formula or proof. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-simplification">
        <title>Simplification</title>
        <p>An implication rule that permits inferring either conjunct from a conjunction. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
      <li xml:id="term-ch10-substitution-instance">
        <title>Substitution instance</title>
        <p>A particular application of a rule schema, produced by replacing each metavariable with a specific well-formed formula. (§10.3)</p>
      </li>
    </dl>

  </section>

  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ch10">
    <title>End-of-Chapter Exercises</title>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch10-s01">
      <title>Exercise Set 1: Identifying Rules</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each line, identify the rule that would justify the
          inference.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s01-01">
        <statement>
          <p>From <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>P</m>, infer <m>Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s01-02">
        <statement>
          <p>From <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m>, infer <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s01-03">
        <statement>
          <p>From <m>P \cdot Q</m>, infer <m>Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s01-04">
        <statement>
          <p>From <m>P</m>, infer <m>P \lor R</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s01-05">
        <statement>
          <p>From <m>P \supset Q</m> and <m>Q \supset R</m>, infer <m>P \supset R</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch10-s02">
      <title>Exercise Set 2: Supply the Missing Line</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Complete each proof by adding the missing line and
          justification.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s02-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s02-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s02-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \lor R</m></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P</m></cell><cell>1 Simp</cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell></cell><cell></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch10-s03">
      <title>Exercise Set 3: Short Proofs</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          Prove each argument valid using the implication rules.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s03-01">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>Q \supset R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \supset R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s03-02">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q \lor S</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s03-03">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \lor Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \lor R</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s03-04">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>P \supset Q</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>R \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>3.</cell><cell><m>P \lor R</m></cell><cell>/ <m>Q \lor S</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s03-05">
        <statement>
          <tabular halign="left" margins="0% 45%">
            <row><cell>1.</cell><cell><m>(P \lor R) \supset S</m></cell><cell></cell></row>
            <row><cell>2.</cell><cell><m>P \cdot Q</m></cell><cell>/ <m>P \cdot S</m></cell></row>
          </tabular>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch10-s04">
      <title>Exercise Set 4: Explain the Strategy</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          For each proof goal, write one or two sentences explaining
          which rule you would try first and why.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s04-01">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>P \cdot Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s04-02">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>{\text{\textasciitilde}}P</m>, and one premise is <m>P \supset Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-s04-03">
        <statement>
          <p>The target is <m>Q \lor S</m>, and you already have <m>Q</m>.</p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

    <exercisegroup xml:id="exgroup-ch10-writing">
      <title>Writing Prompt</title>
      <introduction>
        <p>
          This prompt connects to Field Exercise 10-1.
        </p>
      </introduction>
      <exercise xml:id="ex-ch10-writing-01">
        <statement>
          <p>
            Return to your narrative from Field Exercise 10-1.
            What kind of mistake or dead end did you encounter?
            Was it a pattern-matching failure (not recognizing which
            rule applied), a strategic failure (working forward when
            you should have worked backward), or something else
            entirely? What does this tell you about how you reason
            when the steps are not obvious?
          </p>
        </statement>
      </exercise>
    </exercisegroup>

  </exercises>

</chapter>
